        "content": "<p>Most well-known ecommerce solutions do not support vertical-specific SaaS development, which creates a temptation to develop in-house solutions. Ignoring the risks associated with SaaS platform development can have negative downstream effects in the long-run. According to industry experts, 80%&nbsp;of&nbsp;the budget&nbsp;for homegrown, in-house SaaS solutions is spent on general platform features and only 20% is spent on specific, more valuable niche features -- requiring companies to spend 5 times more to deliver critical MVP functionality.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>Speed-to-market is important for niche solutions. Cost-savings on a technology does not always translate when it comes to performance. Limitations in the capacity of development teams can have an impact on feature functionality as well as development velocity, postponing an immediate return on investment.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>Hidden tangible and intangible costs are the main issue associated with homegrown solutions. There is a significant people-risk as businesses become critically dependent on a few specialists who know how the system works, making it almost impossible to find experienced talent and very difficult to&nbsp;scale.&nbsp;If those employees leave, development can be locked or stagnate for a significant amount of time. &nbsp;The ongoing maintenance risk associated with the solution becomes more and more expensive as vendors assume &nbsp;80% of the responsibility for general platform functionality and non-functional requirements (performance, security,&nbsp;extensibility etc.).</p>\n",
